{
  "texts": [
    "These two additional elements are not only simple factors that control factory production but bring a significant awareness of the importance of the human operator and its environment beyond reaching production targets.Let us assume that: In an I5.0 scenario, we include two major parameters to closely track production level before performing any automatic parameter configurations: the maximum overtime working hours for employees and the maximum pollution rate in the factory.",
    "As opposed to the previous I4.0 model in [53], we now have three conditions to meet before initiating parameters automatic configuration for overtime run:• ORS = Overtime Run Start • Y d = Daily Production Target • OP = Overtime Percentage • X f = Final Production Count • δ = X 0 = Initial Production Count • = Factory Overall Pollution Rate • β = Maximum Factory Pollution Rate • γ = Maximum• Condition 1: Remains the same as defined for the I4.0 system in [53].",
    "We compute the final production count as follows:X f = f n=1 [δ -(X n -1)](1)with n = the number of production hours For the overtime run to start the final production count needs to be below the Overtime Percentage, O Pdefined by the factory:O RS = Y d -(Y d * O P) (2) X f < O RS(3)• Condition 2: In this new condition, the system evaluates the number of missing parts to reach the daily production target.",
    "It computes the number of hours required to produce the missing parts and compare if it does not exceed the maximum overtime working hours for employees.m = Y d -X f (4)where m is the number of missing parts to reach the daily production target.",
    "We can calculate the production time, t in hours, to produce the missing parts as follows:t = m P (5)With respect to the maximum overtime working hours for employees, for overtime production to start, the following condition should be met:t + η < γ (6)Note that we assume that η represents the current overtime working hours done for all employees."
  ]
}